In [[Real property|real estate]] and [[lodging]], an '''amenity''' is something considered to benefit a property <!--Too vague?: (such as its attractiveness, convenience or comfort)--> and thereby increase [[Real estate appraisal|its value]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Carmichael |first1=D. R |edition=10 |year=2003 |title=Accountants' Handbook, Special Industries and Special Topics (Volume 2) |publisher=John Wiley & Sons |page=30 |isbn=0471456179}}</ref> [[Tangible property|Tangible]] amenities can include the number and nature of [[Hotel room|guest rooms]] and the provision of facilities such as [[Elevator|elevators (lifts)]], [[wi-fi]], [[restaurant]]s, [[park]]s, [[Community centre|communal area]]s, [[swimming pool]]s, [[golf course]]s, [[health club]] facilities, party rooms, theater or media rooms, [[bike path]]s or [[Automobile repair shop|garage]]s,<!--The following not usually regarded as an amenity?: [[customer service]]--> while [[Intangible property|intangible]] amenities can include aspects such as well-integrated [[public transport]], pleasant views, nearby activities and a low [[crime rate]]. Within the context of [[environmental economics]], an environmental amenity can include access to [[clean air]] or [[clean water]], or the quality of any other [[environmental good]] that may reduce adverse [[health effects]] for residents or increase their [[economic welfare]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Field |first1=Barry C. |last2=Field |first2=Martha K. |edition=7 |year=2017 |title=Environmental Economics, An Introduction|publisher=McGraw-Hill |page=145-147 |isbn=978-0-07-802189-3}}</ref>
