[[Image:keypadpolling.jpg|thumb|&nbsp;|200px]] '''Keypad Polling''' is a wireless [[Voting|polling]] technology. It can be used to enable community participation in events and to bring a focus to discussion and decision making.<ref>[http://www.ebmtools.org/roadmap/keypad-polling.html Short description of keypad polling]</ref>
One example of this technology comprises a number of hand held [[keypad]]s (similar to TV [[remote control]]s) which communicate using radio frequencies with a base station. This base station is connected to a laptop computer which in turn is linked to a [[Video Graphics Array|VGA]] projector that displays onto a [[projection screen]]. Participants vote anonymously by selecting the number on their keypad that best represents their preference. The result of the group vote is displayed on the projection screen within seconds. The project team also works with clients to prepare suitable questionnaires and produce report documents that analyse voting results. [[Image:keypadpolling2.jpg|thumb|&nbsp;|200px]]
==References== {{reflist}}
[[Category:Polling]] [[Category:Types of polling]] [[Category:Public opinion]]

'''Tagbu''' is an ethnic group in the [[Democratic Republic of the Congo]] and [[Sudan]]. They speak [[Tagbu language|Tagbu]],<ref name=Ethnologue>[http://www.ethnologue.com/language/tbm Ethnologue Languages of the World:Tagbu]. Retrieved January 18, 2016.</ref> a [[Ubangian language]]. Tagbu speakers were estimated to number 17,000 in 2002.<ref name=Ethnologue/>

