{{Infobox book | name = The Twenty Days of Turin | translator = Ramon Glazov | image = | caption = | author = [[Giorgio de Maria]] | cover_artist = | country = Italian | language = | series = | genre = | publisher = | release_date = | media_type = | pages = | isbn = | dewey = | congress = | oclc = | preceded_by = | followed_by = }} '''''The Twenty Days of Turin''''' is a 1975 novel by Italian writer and musician [[Giorgio de Maria]]. Ramon Glazov translated the book into English in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.commonwealmagazine.org/holy-horror|title=Holy Horror|last=Giraldi|first=William|date=1 February 2017|publisher=Commonweal|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref> It concerns a man in [[Turin]] who chooses to investigate a series of unexplained, violent of events that occurred a decade earlier.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vulture.com/article/best-dystopian-books.html|title=100 Great Works OF Dystopian Fiction|publisher=Vulture|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref>
It has been referred to as "remarkably prescient"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/2017/02/08/507168482/nothing-is-quite-what-it-seems-in-surreal-unsettling-twenty-days|title=Nothing Is Quite What It Seems In Surreal, Unsettling 'Twenty Days'|last=Sheehan|first=Jason|date=8 February 2017|publisher=NPR|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref> and has garnered comparisons to the works of [[H.P. Lovecraft]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lareviewofbooks.org/article/foul-small-minded-deities-giorgio-de-maria/#!|title="Foul, Small-Minded Deities": On Giorgio De Maria’s "The Twenty Days of Turin"|last=Berard|first=Peter|date=7 February 2017|publisher=Los Angeles Review of Books|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref> and [[Thomas Pynchon]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.commonwealmagazine.org/twenty-days-turin|title='The Twenty Days of Turin': An Italian Classic's Chilling Prescience|last=Ripatrazone|first=Nick|date=4 January 2017|publisher=Commonweal|accessdate=12 October 2018}}</ref>
